postcontent: Rifle is unissued and was manufactured from parts available at the Lithgow factory in Australia. Rifle is in pristine condition and appears to never have been fired.Should be seen as a collectible that can and should be fired!Includes: one removable magazine, bayonet, bayonet sheath and canvas covers for both the action and the muzzle. (a) Bayonet and bayonet sheath: - 16 5/8" long. It has a Lithgow 1907 bayonet sheath. The bayonet stamp markings: Line 1: MKI, Line 2: NWPLine 3: 42(b) A Lee-Enfield canvas action cover. It covers the area of the bolt action, the trigger and the removable magazine. (c) A Lee-Enfield canvas muzzle cover. Dated 1952, it appears to be in near new condition and has only been used with this rifle.RIFLE MARKINGSThe rifle has a coachwood stock. Coachwood is a slender tree of the rain forests of Australia and New Guinea, with close-grained timber that has a characteristic caramel scent and is used for cabinetmaking and veneers today.(a) Serial Number: The serial number appears in three locations: (1) Right side of the chamber where the barrel screws in (2) Flatside rear edge of the bolt handle (3) Nosecap for the bayonet. Each of the serial numbers start with the letter "A" and is followed by 4 digits.(b) Rifle has a brass butt plate.(c) Beneath the bolt handle are the following markings, it is in 5 lines: (1) MA (2) LITHGOW (3) SMLE (stands for Small Magazine, Lee-Enfield but called Smelly) (4) III* (5) 1945.(d) The marking "BA" is found in four locations on this rifle: (1) On the left side of the trigger (2) The bottom of the trigger guard (3) On the receiver behind the bolt handle. (4) The front right side of the bolt. (BA stands for Rifle Factory #2 Bathurst).(e) Marking on the right wing protector of the rear sight is "OA". (OA stands for Rifle Factory #3 Orange).(f) Marking on the metal band that surrounds the wood forestock that holds the front sling keeper are the letters "MA". (MA stands for rifles made after 1926).(g) Stamped into the wood on the bottom side of the front forestock about 2" back from the bayonet mount is "SLAZ 43". (SLAZ stands for the Slazenger Factory produced in 1943).(h) On the safety, is the Roman Numeral; III.(i) The underside of the flip-up rear sights are marked WA 43. ("WA" stands for the factory at Wellington Annex and 43 is 1943.)The wood stock is fantastic condition, as well as the metal bluing. This rifle may have not been fired at all and is in to new condition.Selling price for the rifle, removable magazine, canvas covers for the action, as well as the muzzle, and the bayonet and sheath - - - all for $600.Location: South Metro area of Denver, COTerms of Sale:-please, no trade offers at this time

title: For Sale:  Panzerfaust 30 (Klein) Replica
postcontent: Introduced in 1943, the Panzerfaust Klein (Translated literally to mean: Tank Fist Small) was a forerunner of the Panzerfaust Gross (Tank Fist Large) or Panzerfaust 60m rocket. This ingenious throw away Rocket and Launcher was one of Hitler's last ditch weapons adopted by the Nazis to try and repel the invading Allies on both the Eastern and Western fronts. "Most authors agree that production of the Panzerfaust Klein was halted somewhere in early 1944, due to its insufficient penetration of armor and replaced by the larger model." This inert display reproduction faithfully replicates this classic weapon but none of the internal working parts are included. Each Rocket comes in full size steel construction and is externally accurate including the flexible stabilizing fins. It even has the stuck on replicated instruction label, as issued on the originals. Includes all steel launcher based on an original sample, correct Panzerfaust Klein trigger assembly (which is different than the 60M Trigger Assembly). This trigger assembly has the correct leaf sight and pull pin. For added authenticity, both Rocket and Launcher are now offered in the correct German WW2 Ordinance Tan or "Gelbbraun" color with red stencil on launcher which reads "Vorsicht! Starker Feuerstrahl!". They have purposely painted this set to resemble a genuine Panzerfaust, meaning the paint is not and should not provide 100% smooth coverage, these are intended to look like the REAL THING based on the original sample.Shipping is extra.
